@P@PelemusMcSoynd you probably have a busy life and still found time to do research to make a great game! My brother is always the D&D DM and he’s devoted. It’s crazy—but entirely unsurprising—that ordinary fans with their own lives and jobs put in more effort and creativity than wealthy entertainment executives and directors who are being paid millions to create products based on that material.

My other favorite book series was made a disastrously awful TV show by Disney. The director confidently said he had never read the books. It showed.

I would be so embarrassed. Even if I hated the source material, I would immerse myself in it and understand why it was so compelling.

@rednekcrazzy938 Except this doesn't appear to be very consistent. Hermoine is not attractive in the books, Ron isn't an idiot, Snape isn't supposed to be old and Dumbledore was never gay. It seems to me that the fans are very selective in what should be consistent and what shouldn't.

As for the black victim narrative...I too hate that and I was hoping it wouldn't be the case but the more I read about this actor the more it seems like they will do just that so I probably won't even watch this. Trust me I hate it more than you do. I don't think they needed to do a race thing or even bring that up at all but Hollywood as it is now is is just a machine for activists.

To address the race swapping thing. As I said above I don't think it needs to be about race. If they had an open casting call and the best actor stood out was him, why would I care what color he is if he can personify the character. Like I said...I no longer believe that's the case with all the comments coming out from the cast and crew but it shouldn't matter unless his character is specifically tied to that.

